[{"sha":"aa99c6831f120cef77b6421b3c6eab01dcea14f1","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Add missing algebraic simplifications for batch-dots.

1. Make dot(a,b)^T => dot(b,a) work for batch-dot (where ^T flips the order of
   the non-batch dims).

2. Make dot(a^T, b^T) => dot(b,a)^T work for batch-dot.

3. Add a new simplification:

     dot(reorder_batch_dims(a), reorder_batch_dims(b)) =>
     reorder_batch_dims(dot(a,b)).

(The last simplification is implemented as part of the second one.)

Change-Id: Ie04a2faefb1c1976b40554d1c12ac8d1d1d7e7d8","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/efa703a6b9c1883022d2600eadffe989edc5d605"},{"sha":"d137e0f6487351ee6fb061e701eab4cf596b9c35","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Remove nondeterminism that occurs due to asynchronicity.

Certain datasets, like Prefetch, can run dataset ops asynchronously by using a background thread to run the input pipeline in the background while other non-dataset ops are running. This can cause nondeterminism when the input pipeline has map or interleave or filter datasets whose function has stateful ops. Such stateful ops run in parallel with ops running outside the dataset, so the order stateful ops are run is nondeterministic. To solve this, the make_deterministic pass removes or rewrites dataset ops such as Prefetch when there are problematic stateful ops in the input pipeline.

Also, tests in make_deterministic_test.py no longer set `apply_default_optimizations=False`. It is important to test that the default optimizations do not introduce nondeterminism.

[{"sha":"1af996d05a12f337c7eacf43c7c5ce4de99d7082","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Unnested variadic reduction emitter

Only works when tree reduction is enabled.

Previously, only the elemental emitter for variadic reduction was available.

Conceptually, variadic reduction processes an array of tuples instead of an
array of scalars. This input is represented as multiple input arrays.
Since the reduction function in variadic reduction has to produce a tuple, it
can not be used with atomics, and consequently requires tree reduction.

The algorithm is the same as for the normal reduction, but generating the call
to the reduction computation is a bit more difficult since it has to return a
tuple which can not be done directly. Instead, we use the same trick which was
already used in the elemental emitter: the computation function gets N output
to them.

[{"sha":"d137e0f6487351ee6fb061e701eab4cf596b9c35","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Remove nondeterminism that occurs due to asynchronicity.

Certain datasets, like Prefetch, can run dataset ops asynchronously by using a background thread to run the input pipeline in the background while other non-dataset ops are running. This can cause nondeterminism when the input pipeline has map or interleave or filter datasets whose function has stateful ops. Such stateful ops run in parallel with ops running outside the dataset, so the order stateful ops are run is nondeterministic. To solve this, the make_deterministic pass removes or rewrites dataset ops such as Prefetch when there are problematic stateful ops in the input pipeline.

Also, tests in make_deterministic_test.py no longer set `apply_default_optimizations=False`. It is important to test that the default optimizations do not introduce nondeterminism.

[{"sha":"d7224170dadde0fff233a7d7a1e1cbeee51700cf","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Report ActionReasons when we plan to delete "orphans"

There are a few different reasons why a resource instance tracked in the
prior state might be considered an "orphan", but previously we reported
them all identically in the planned changes.

In order to help users understand the reason for a surprising planned
delete, we'll now try to specify an additional reason for the planned
deletion, covering all of the main reasons why that could happen.

This commit only introduces the new detail to the plans.Changes result,
though it also incidentally exposes it as part of the JSON plan result
in order to keep that working without returning errors in these new
cases. We'll expose this information in the human-oriented UI output in
a subsequent commit.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d7224170dadde0fff233a7d7a1e1cbeee51700cf"},{"sha":"6d94e9c1e2927867c9d4440a197b5fc12efc399c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Include deletion reasons in plan report

The core runtime is now able to specify a reason for some situations when
Terraform plans to delete a resource instance.

This commit makes that information visible in the human-oriented UI. A
previous commit already made the underlying data informing these new hints
visible as part of the machine-oriented (JSON) plan output.

This also removes the bold formatting from the existing "has moved to"
hints, because subjectively it seemed like the result was emphasizing too
many parts of the output and thus somewhat defeating the benefit of the
emphasis in trying to create additional visual hierarchy for sighted users
running Terraform in a terminal. Now only the first line containing the
main action statement will be in bold, and all of the parenthesized
follow-up notes will be unformatted.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/6d94e9c1e2927867c9d4440a197b5fc12efc399c"}]

The whole point of UniqueKey is to deal with the fact that we have some
distinct address types which have an identical string representation, but
unfortunately that fact caused us to not notice that we'd incorrectly
made AbsResource.UniqueKey return a no-key instance UniqueKey instead of
its own distinct unique key type.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Juneezee/terraform/commits/d054102d38c54be67edccdd8f191e1beecd68252"},{"sha":"83f03766739394cafd5983ebc0d5fb46b2a20133","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"refactoring: ApplyMoves new return type

When we originally stubbed ApplyMoves we didn't know yet how exactly we'd
be using the result, so we made it a double-indexed map allowing looking
up moves in both directions.

However, in practice we only actually need to look up old addresses by new
addresses, and so this commit first removes the double indexing so that
each move is only represented by one element in the map.

We also need to describe situations where a move was blocked, because in
a future commit we'll generate some warnings in those cases. Therefore
ApplyMoves now returns a MoveResults object which contains both a map of
changes and a map of blocks. The map of blocks isn't used yet as of this
commit, but we'll use it in a later commit to produce warnings within
the "terraform" package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Juneezee/terraform/commits/83f03766739394cafd5983ebc0d5fb46b2a20133"},{"sha":"3f1c15c792ff18496774ecf951818068ab77c3ba","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Upgrade to Go 1.17.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Juneezee/terraform/commits/3f1c15c792ff18496774ecf951818068ab77c3ba"},{"sha":"d14bbbb6f2a86118015b3de46246e14cdb4977b9","author":{"name":"hc-github-team-tf-core","email":"2b2269f92a0d9a665710b39784c31ab099da0712@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Release v1.1.0-alpha20210922","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Juneezee/terraform/commits/d14bbbb6f2a86118015b3de46246e14cdb4977b9"},{"sha":"cd1d30ea95a0f16818c5d7915fd1983994a26b0d","author":{"name":"hc-github-team-tf-core","email":"2b2269f92a0d9a665710b39784c31ab099da0712@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Cleanup after v1.1.0-alpha20210922 release","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Juneezee/terraform/commits/cd1d30ea95a0f16818c5d7915fd1983994a26b0d"}]

Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

When migrating some internal tests I found it annoying that I couldn't
return anything from the `act` scope. You would have to declare the
variable on the outside then assign to it. But this doesn't play well
with type systems — when you use the variable, you have to check
the type.

Before:

```js
let renderer;
act(() => {
  renderer = ReactTestRenderer.create(<App />);
})

// Type system can't tell that renderer is never undefined
renderer?.root.findByType(Component);
```

After:

```js
const renderer = await act(() => {
  return ReactTestRenderer.create(<App />);
})
renderer.root.findByType(Component);
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/buoyantair/react/commits/cae635054e17a6f107a39d328649137b83f25972"},{"sha":"d483463bc86555decb3e8caa18459d1d0f7c0148","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Updated scripts and config to replace "master" with "main" branch (#21768)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/buoyantair/react/commits/d483463bc86555decb3e8caa18459d1d0f7c0148"},{"sha":"83f38d07689b8b750b7d96e17647a8978b836154","author":{"name":"dependabot[bot]","email":"1c358da00a777d4e9898c1280ab801e2df165188@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Bump ecstatic from 2.2.1 to 2.2.2 in /scripts/bench (#20468)

Change-Id: I703e70eef24cfc48747ad213ecc124796e32ea2a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/36740075535552ce83341cc866a4331c73a7e5c7"},{"sha":"12243264d62e409796c2a2e643b251c00a8ef4d2","author":{"name":"Saurabh Saxena","email":"a06419f1d29903870f8bf4863dbb6b72d69bfd5a@google.com"},"message":"Do not jit compile wrapped functions, run them via FLR instead. This is needed because certain ops that are placed on XLA devices do not support compilation. Running via FLR ensures we execute these ops the same way they would have run in eager mode. Long-term this should be handled by outside compilation but that is not available on GPU right now.

Place the NodeDef in the FunctionDef on the device that eager mode placement would have picked for the eager op. Certain ops e.g. RangeDataset are placed on GPU in eager mode but expect to be run on CPU. Eager mode placement understands this and picks the CPU device in this case, graph mode placer raises an error. For backwards compatibility we go with the choice made by eager mode placement. This requires us to trace a FunctionDef per-device. Optimizing the number of traces has been filed as future work.

Change-Id: I34d76747acf04f6939cc7d6ebb4236629841e25c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/03062791a99d9b04026619a7a3657d7ffc02fa53"},{"sha":"1af996d05a12f337c7eacf43c7c5ce4de99d7082","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Unnested variadic reduction emitter

Only works when tree reduction is enabled.

Previously, only the elemental emitter for variadic reduction was available.

Conceptually, variadic reduction processes an array of tuples instead of an
array of scalars. This input is represented as multiple input arrays.
Since the reduction function in variadic reduction has to produce a tuple, it
can not be used with atomics, and consequently requires tree reduction.

The algorithm is the same as for the normal reduction, but generating the call
to the reduction computation is a bit more difficult since it has to return a
tuple which can not be done directly. Instead, we use the same trick which was
already used in the elemental emitter: the computation function gets N output

PiperOrigin-RevId: 398399168
Change-Id: I34d76747acf04f6939cc7d6ebb4236629841e25c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/03062791a99d9b04026619a7a3657d7ffc02fa53"},{"sha":"1af996d05a12f337c7eacf43c7c5ce4de99d7082","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Unnested variadic reduction emitter

Only works when tree reduction is enabled.

Previously, only the elemental emitter for variadic reduction was available.

Conceptually, variadic reduction processes an array of tuples instead of an
array of scalars. This input is represented as multiple input arrays.
Since the reduction function in variadic reduction has to produce a tuple, it
can not be used with atomics, and consequently requires tree reduction.

The algorithm is the same as for the normal reduction, but generating the call
to the reduction computation is a bit more difficult since it has to return a
tuple which can not be done directly. Instead, we use the same trick which was
already used in the elemental emitter: the computation function gets N output
to them.

Change-Id: I703e70eef24cfc48747ad213ecc124796e32ea2a","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/36740075535552ce83341cc866a4331c73a7e5c7"},{"sha":"12243264d62e409796c2a2e643b251c00a8ef4d2","author":{"name":"Saurabh Saxena","email":"a06419f1d29903870f8bf4863dbb6b72d69bfd5a@google.com"},"message":"Do not jit compile wrapped functions, run them via FLR instead. This is needed because certain ops that are placed on XLA devices do not support compilation. Running via FLR ensures we execute these ops the same way they would have run in eager mode. Long-term this should be handled by outside compilation but that is not available on GPU right now.

Place the NodeDef in the FunctionDef on the device that eager mode placement would have picked for the eager op. Certain ops e.g. RangeDataset are placed on GPU in eager mode but expect to be run on CPU. Eager mode placement understands this and picks the CPU device in this case, graph mode placer raises an error. For backwards compatibility we go with the choice made by eager mode placement. This requires us to trace a FunctionDef per-device. Optimizing the number of traces has been filed as future work.

Change-Id: I3d9831c7c6695adc832d49e87e328caaa737f179","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/a749bda1036e24ef97ea4730ff85668b6246c4a0"},{"sha":"a4e574e6a53cc459f7ac29393c35b0342ce0bb77","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Move CollTaskParams into CollGroupParams

CollTaskParams only store whether a device is local or not. CollTaskParams::is_local corresponds to the devices, instead of the tasks. It makes more sense to fold CollTaskParams simply into CollGroupParams.

CollTaskParams used to populated as part of CompleteInstance. After the move it will be populated as par of CompleteGroup, which also makes more sense.

providing also good compression ratios.  The fast decoder makes it
suitable for container images, as decompressing the tarballs is a very
expensive operation.

https://github.com/opencontainers/image-spec/pull/788 added support
for zstd to the OCI image specs.

be using the result, so we made it a double-indexed map allowing looking
up moves in both directions.

addresses, and so this commit first removes the double indexing so that
each move is only represented by one element in the map.

We also need to describe situations where a move was blocked, because in
a future commit we'll generate some warnings in those cases. Therefore
ApplyMoves now returns a MoveResults object which contains both a map of
changes and a map of blocks. The map of blocks isn't used yet as of this

Since the URL is showing 404 error and alternative URL is not present in the repo for README fine removed URL https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/tree/master/tensorflow/core/profiler/README.md from the file.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/9bd3c3cef915097f19859c096db0a8b260307c7b"},{"sha":"1af996d05a12f337c7eacf43c7c5ce4de99d7082","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Unnested variadic reduction emitter

Only works when tree reduction is enabled.

Previously, only the elemental emitter for variadic reduction was available.

Conceptually, variadic reduction processes an array of tuples instead of an
array of scalars. This input is represented as multiple input arrays.
Since the reduction function in variadic reduction has to produce a tuple, it
can not be used with atomics, and consequently requires tree reduction.

The algorithm is the same as for the normal reduction, but generating the call
to the reduction computation is a bit more difficult since it has to return a
tuple which can not be done directly. Instead, we use the same trick which was
already used in the elemental emitter: the computation function gets N output
to them.

[{"sha":"3a50d95573b7ebdf723e08f6f78c99faf811da0b","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Never attach ping listeners in legacy Suspense (#22407)

I noticed a weird branch where we attach a ping listener even in legacy
mode. It's weird because this shouldn't be necessary. Fallbacks always
synchronously commit in legacy mode, so pings never happen. (A "ping" is
when a suspended promise resolves before the fallback has committed.)

It took me a moment to remember why this case exists, but it's related
to React.lazy.

There's a special case where we suspend while reconciling the children
of a Suspense boundary's inner Offscreen wrapper fiber. This happens
when a React.lazy component is a direct child of a Suspense boundary.

Suspense boundaries are implemented as multiple fibers, but they are a
single conceptual unit. The legacy mode behavior where we pretend the
suspended fiber committed as `null` won't work, because in this case the
"suspended" fiber is the inner Offscreen wrapper.

Because the contents of the boundary haven't started rendering yet (i.e.
nothing in the tree has partially rendered) we can switch to the
regular, concurrent mode behavior: mark the boundary with ShouldCapture
and enter the unwind phase.

However, even though we're switching to the concurrent mode behavior, we
don't need to attach a ping listener. So I refactored the logic so that
it doesn't escape back into the regular path.

It's not really a big deal that we attach an unncessary ping listener,
since this case is so unusual. The motivation is not performance related
— it's to make the logic clearer, because I'm about to add another case
where we trigger a Suspense boundary without attaching a ping listener.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/3a50d95573b7ebdf723e08f6f78c99faf811da0b"}]

[{"sha":"af84ca8653c555da843b8528076796b313236d9d","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Report a warning if any moves get blocked

In most cases Terraform will be able to automatically fully resolve all
of the pending move statements before creating a plan, but there are some
edge cases where we can end up wanting to move one object to a location
where another object is already declared.

One relatively-obvious example is if someone uses "terraform state mv" in
order to create a set of resource instance bindings that could never have
arising in normal Terraform use.

A less obvious example arises from the interactions between moves at
different levels of granularity. If we are both moving a module to a new
address and moving a resource into an instance of the new module at the
same time, the old module might well have already had a resource of the
same name and so the resource move will be unresolvable.

In these situations Terraform will move the objects as far as possible,
but because it's never valid for a move "from" address to still be
declared in the configuration Terraform will inevitably always plan to
destroy the objects that didn't find a final home. To give some additional
explanation for that result, here we'll add a warning which describes
what happened.

This is not a particularly actionable warning because we don't really
have enough information to guess what the user intended, but we do at
least prompt that they might be able to use the "terraform state" family
of subcommands to repair the ambiguous situation before planning, if they
want a different result than what Terraform proposed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/af84ca8653c555da843b8528076796b313236d9d"}]

Change-Id: I703e70eef24cfc48747ad213ecc124796e32ea2a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/tensorflow/commits/36740075535552ce83341cc866a4331c73a7e5c7"},{"sha":"12243264d62e409796c2a2e643b251c00a8ef4d2","author":{"name":"Saurabh Saxena","email":"a06419f1d29903870f8bf4863dbb6b72d69bfd5a@google.com"},"message":"Do not jit compile wrapped functions, run them via FLR instead. This is needed because certain ops that are placed on XLA devices do not support compilation. Running via FLR ensures we execute these ops the same way they would have run in eager mode. Long-term this should be handled by outside compilation but that is not available on GPU right now.

Place the NodeDef in the FunctionDef on the device that eager mode placement would have picked for the eager op. Certain ops e.g. RangeDataset are placed on GPU in eager mode but expect to be run on CPU. Eager mode placement understands this and picks the CPU device in this case, graph mode placer raises an error. For backwards compatibility we go with the choice made by eager mode placement. This requires us to trace a FunctionDef per-device. Optimizing the number of traces has been filed as future work.

     reorder_batch_dims(dot(a,b)).

[{"sha":"5cedfd22400f212644bb47236d300ccdc17b3a74","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Never attach ping listeners in legacy Suspense

I noticed a weird branch where we attach a ping listener even in legacy
mode. It's weird because this shouldn't be necessary. Fallbacks always
synchronously commit in legacy mode, so pings never happen. (A "ping" is
when a suspended promise resolves before the fallback has committed.)

It took me a moment to remember why this case exists, but it's related
to React.lazy.

There's a special case where we suspend while reconciling the children
of a Suspense boundary's inner Offscreen wrapper fiber. This happens
when a React.lazy component is a direct child of a Suspense boundary.

Suspense boundaries are implemented as multiple fibers, but they are a
single conceptual unit. The legacy mode behavior where we pretend the
suspended fiber committed as `null` won't work, because in this case the
"suspended" fiber is the inner Offscreen wrapper.

Because the contents of the boundary haven't started rendering yet (i.e.
nothing in the tree has partially rendered) we can switch to the
regular, concurrent mode behavior: mark the boundary with ShouldCapture
and enter the unwind phase.

However, even though we're switching to the concurrent mode behavior, we
don't need to attach a ping listener. So I refactored the logic so that
it doesn't escape back into the regular path.

It's not really a big deal that we attach an unncessary ping listener,
since this case is so unusual. The motivation is not performance related
— it's to make the logic clearer, because I'm about to add another case
where we trigger a Suspense boundary without attaching a ping listener.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/5cedfd22400f212644bb47236d300ccdc17b3a74"}]

Change-Id: I703e70eef24cfc48747ad213ecc124796e32ea2a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/36740075535552ce83341cc866a4331c73a7e5c7"},{"sha":"12243264d62e409796c2a2e643b251c00a8ef4d2","author":{"name":"Saurabh Saxena","email":"a06419f1d29903870f8bf4863dbb6b72d69bfd5a@google.com"},"message":"Do not jit compile wrapped functions, run them via FLR instead. This is needed because certain ops that are placed on XLA devices do not support compilation. Running via FLR ensures we execute these ops the same way they would have run in eager mode. Long-term this should be handled by outside compilation but that is not available on GPU right now.

Place the NodeDef in the FunctionDef on the device that eager mode placement would have picked for the eager op. Certain ops e.g. RangeDataset are placed on GPU in eager mode but expect to be run on CPU. Eager mode placement understands this and picks the CPU device in this case, graph mode placer raises an error. For backwards compatibility we go with the choice made by eager mode placement. This requires us to trace a FunctionDef per-device. Optimizing the number of traces has been filed as future work.

This commit dramatically improves the performance of the hook names feature by replacing the source-map-js integration with custom mapping code built on top of sourcemap-codec. While implementing this code, I also uncovered a problem with the way we were caching source-map metadata that was causing us to potential parse the same source-map multiple times. [{"sha":"d174d063d13d428ad4002474cb560464a7f70f45","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Hook names optimizations (#22403)

This commit dramatically improves the performance of the hook names feature by replacing the source-map-js integration with custom mapping code built on top of sourcemap-codec. Based on my own benchmarking, this makes parsing 3-4 times faster. (The bulk of these changes are in SourceMapConsumer.js.)

While implementing this code, I also uncovered a problem with the way we were caching source-map metadata that was causing us to potential parse the same source-map multiple times. (I addressed this in a separate commit for easier reviewing. The bulk of these changes are in parseSourceAndMetadata.js.)

Altogether these changes dramatically improve the performance of the hooks parsing code.

One additional thing we could look into if the source-map download still remains a large bottleneck would be to stream it and decode the mappings array while it streams in rather than in one synchronous chunk after the full source-map has been downloaded.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sanketshah19/react/commits/d174d063d13d428ad4002474cb560464a7f70f45"}]

[{"sha":"3c6c5c1465ee89c5248db4a8a2eef5962d0b5c87","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Don't return other errors if move statements are invalid

Because our validation rules depend on some dynamic results produced by
actually running the plan, we deal with moves in a "backwards" order where
we try to apply them first -- ignoring anything strange we might find --
and then validate the original statements only after planning.

An unfortunate consequence of that approach is that when the move
statements are invalid it's likely that move execution will not fully
complete, and so the generated plan is likely to be incorrect and might
well include errors resulting from the unresolved moves.

To mitigate that, here we let any move validation errors supersede all
other diagnostics that the plan phase might've generated, in the hope that
it'll help the user focus on fixing the incorrect move statements without
creating confusing by reporting errors that only appeared as a quick of
how Terraform worked around the invalid move statements earlier.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/3c6c5c1465ee89c5248db4a8a2eef5962d0b5c87"}]

Change-Id: I703e70eef24cfc48747ad213ecc124796e32ea2a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jatin837/tensorflow/commits/36740075535552ce83341cc866a4331c73a7e5c7"},{"sha":"12243264d62e409796c2a2e643b251c00a8ef4d2","author":{"name":"Saurabh Saxena","email":"a06419f1d29903870f8bf4863dbb6b72d69bfd5a@google.com"},"message":"Do not jit compile wrapped functions, run them via FLR instead. This is needed because certain ops that are placed on XLA devices do not support compilation. Running via FLR ensures we execute these ops the same way they would have run in eager mode. Long-term this should be handled by outside compilation but that is not available on GPU right now.

Place the NodeDef in the FunctionDef on the device that eager mode placement would have picked for the eager op. Certain ops e.g. RangeDataset are placed on GPU in eager mode but expect to be run on CPU. Eager mode placement understands this and picks the CPU device in this case, graph mode placer raises an error. For backwards compatibility we go with the choice made by eager mode placement. This requires us to trace a FunctionDef per-device. Optimizing the number of traces has been filed as future work.

fix api compatibility test failures","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pcf000/tensorflow/commits/1b0f8973fa0a47169ce716ff8889c592846f0c06"},{"sha":"db829d97c69d76b3a842a8c898fc81b55ed76ed6","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Introduce a cache to avoid O(n^2) behavior with GPU MOF.

Some models have many multi-output fusion opportunities.  When we evaluate
these, we do an O(n^2) iteration over all pairs of nodes in an equivalence
class.

Before this change, we would recompute the shared memory required for each
fusion, and the number of unnested reductions in each fusion, O(n^2) times.
Computing these is tantamount to iterating over the whole fusion node, so is
especially expensive when the fusion is large.

Now we cache these values, so we compute them only O(n) times.

[{"sha":"d137e0f6487351ee6fb061e701eab4cf596b9c35","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Remove nondeterminism that occurs due to asynchronicity.

Certain datasets, like Prefetch, can run dataset ops asynchronously by using a background thread to run the input pipeline in the background while other non-dataset ops are running. This can cause nondeterminism when the input pipeline has map or interleave or filter datasets whose function has stateful ops. Such stateful ops run in parallel with ops running outside the dataset, so the order stateful ops are run is nondeterministic. To solve this, the make_deterministic pass removes or rewrites dataset ops such as Prefetch when there are problematic stateful ops in the input pipeline.

Also, tests in make_deterministic_test.py no longer set `apply_default_optimizations=False`. It is important to test that the default optimizations do not introduce nondeterminism.

[{"sha":"60bc7aa05dbd99dd9e1809a4bec7d1f392f5730d","author":{"name":"Chris Arcand","email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com"},"message":"command: Auto-select single workspace if necessary

When initializing a backend, if the currently selected workspace does
not exist, the user is prompted to select from the list of workspaces
the backend provides.

Instead, we should automatically select the only workspace available
_if_ that's all that's there.

improvments with Terraform Cloud in potentially removing the implicit

configuration is mapped to a single TFC workspace.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/60bc7aa05dbd99dd9e1809a4bec7d1f392f5730d"},{"sha":"171cdbbf939e12153d93a1c06806a7ad507ced3c","author":{"name":"Chris Arcand","email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com"},"message":"command: Clean up testInputResponseMap before failing on unused answers

Auto select single workspace when necessary","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/db6ca866fc0f10fa9355cfd53e5d58b4fe1c61c0"},{"sha":"7b99861b1c0acf65ab994e06be13eb08ac6f353f","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"refactoring: Don't implicitly move for resources with for_each

Our previous rule for implicitly moving from IntKey(0) to NoKey would
apply that move even when the current resource configuration uses
for_each, because we were only considering whether "count" were set.

Previously this was relatively harmless because the resource instance in
question would end up planned for deletion anyway: neither an IntKey nor
a NoKey are valid keys for for_each.

Now that we're going to be announcing these moves explicitly in the UI,
it would be confusing to see Terraform report that IntKey moved to NoKey
in a situation where the config changed from count to for_each, so to
address that we'll only generate the implied statement if neither
repetition argument is set.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/7b99861b1c0acf65ab994e06be13eb08ac6f353f"},{"sha":"a1a713cf281d9d07ef2dad96d625703051e3e1c6","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Report ActionReasons when we plan to delete "orphans"

There are a few different reasons why a resource instance tracked in the
prior state might be considered an "orphan", but previously we reported
them all identically in the planned changes.

In order to help users understand the reason for a surprising planned
delete, we'll now try to specify an additional reason for the planned
deletion, covering all of the main reasons why that could happen.

This commit only introduces the new detail to the plans.Changes result,
though it also incidentally exposes it as part of the JSON plan result
in order to keep that working without returning errors in these new
cases. We'll expose this information in the human-oriented UI output in
a subsequent commit.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/a1a713cf281d9d07ef2dad96d625703051e3e1c6"},{"sha":"04f9e7148cd5cc8fa74ccd8af0c8dd2472d3a7f2","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Include deletion reasons in plan report

The core runtime is now able to specify a reason for some situations when
Terraform plans to delete a resource instance.

This commit makes that information visible in the human-oriented UI. A
previous commit already made the underlying data informing these new hints
visible as part of the machine-oriented (JSON) plan output.

This also removes the bold formatting from the existing "has moved to"
hints, because subjectively it seemed like the result was emphasizing too
many parts of the output and thus somewhat defeating the benefit of the
emphasis in trying to create additional visual hierarchy for sighted users
running Terraform in a terminal. Now only the first line containing the
main action statement will be in bold, and all of the parenthesized
follow-up notes will be unformatted.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/04f9e7148cd5cc8fa74ccd8af0c8dd2472d3a7f2"},{"sha":"1bff623fd9578df46a64ac984d64195d1c30554c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Report a warning if any moves get blocked

In most cases Terraform will be able to automatically fully resolve all
of the pending move statements before creating a plan, but there are some
edge cases where we can end up wanting to move one object to a location
where another object is already declared.

One relatively-obvious example is if someone uses "terraform state mv" in
order to create a set of resource instance bindings that could never have
arising in normal Terraform use.

A less obvious example arises from the interactions between moves at
different levels of granularity. If we are both moving a module to a new
address and moving a resource into an instance of the new module at the
same time, the old module might well have already had a resource of the
same name and so the resource move will be unresolvable.

In these situations Terraform will move the objects as far as possible,
but because it's never valid for a move "from" address to still be
declared in the configuration Terraform will inevitably always plan to
destroy the objects that didn't find a final home. To give some additional
explanation for that result, here we'll add a warning which describes
what happened.

This is not a particularly actionable warning because we don't really
have enough information to guess what the user intended, but we do at
least prompt that they might be able to use the "terraform state" family
of subcommands to repair the ambiguous situation before planning, if they
want a different result than what Terraform proposed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/1bff623fd9578df46a64ac984d64195d1c30554c"},{"sha":"d97ef10bb8cc01ab6975590ea6a410a6f586a64e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Don't return other errors if move statements are invalid

Because our validation rules depend on some dynamic results produced by
actually running the plan, we deal with moves in a "backwards" order where
we try to apply them first -- ignoring anything strange we might find --
and then validate the original statements only after planning.

An unfortunate consequence of that approach is that when the move
statements are invalid it's likely that move execution will not fully
complete, and so the generated plan is likely to be incorrect and might
well include errors resulting from the unresolved moves.

To mitigate that, here we let any move validation errors supersede all
other diagnostics that the plan phase might've generated, in the hope that
it'll help the user focus on fixing the incorrect move statements without
creating confusing by reporting errors that only appeared as a quick of
how Terraform worked around the invalid move statements earlier.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/d97ef10bb8cc01ab6975590ea6a410a6f586a64e"},{"sha":"0f76e3a4e1eb1078ec19e17ea5834ea296365f93","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/0f76e3a4e1eb1078ec19e17ea5834ea296365f93"},{"sha":"5d620303eb1b6bb6562a634991f5a59bc79902ea","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/terraform/commits/5d620303eb1b6bb6562a634991f5a59bc79902ea"}]

[{"sha":"118317da9d3ee7d82bfefc978711ca1077e34631","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Include deletion reasons in plan report

The core runtime is now able to specify a reason for some situations when
Terraform plans to delete a resource instance.

This commit makes that information visible in the human-oriented UI. A
previous commit already made the underlying data informing these new hints
visible as part of the machine-oriented (JSON) plan output.

This also removes the bold formatting from the existing "has moved to"
hints, because subjectively it seemed like the result was emphasizing too
many parts of the output and thus somewhat defeating the benefit of the
emphasis in trying to create additional visual hierarchy for sighted users
running Terraform in a terminal. Now only the first line containing the
main action statement will be in bold, and all of the parenthesized
follow-up notes will be unformatted.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/118317da9d3ee7d82bfefc978711ca1077e34631"}]

[{"sha":"b5f93388bc08a5ed7b443a01dff9511ef165a505","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Include deletion reasons in plan report

The core runtime is now able to specify a reason for some situations when
Terraform plans to delete a resource instance.

This commit makes that information visible in the human-oriented UI. A
previous commit already made the underlying data informing these new hints
visible as part of the machine-oriented (JSON) plan output.

This also removes the bold formatting from the existing "has moved to"
hints, because subjectively it seemed like the result was emphasizing too
many parts of the output and thus somewhat defeating the benefit of the
emphasis in trying to create additional visual hierarchy for sighted users
running Terraform in a terminal. Now only the first line containing the
main action statement will be in bold, and all of the parenthesized
follow-up notes will be unformatted.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5f93388bc08a5ed7b443a01dff9511ef165a505"}]

[{"sha":"7b99861b1c0acf65ab994e06be13eb08ac6f353f","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"refactoring: Don't implicitly move for resources with for_each

Our previous rule for implicitly moving from IntKey(0) to NoKey would
apply that move even when the current resource configuration uses
for_each, because we were only considering whether "count" were set.

Previously this was relatively harmless because the resource instance in
question would end up planned for deletion anyway: neither an IntKey nor
a NoKey are valid keys for for_each.

Now that we're going to be announcing these moves explicitly in the UI,
it would be confusing to see Terraform report that IntKey moved to NoKey
in a situation where the config changed from count to for_each, so to
address that we'll only generate the implied statement if neither
repetition argument is set.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/7b99861b1c0acf65ab994e06be13eb08ac6f353f"},{"sha":"a1a713cf281d9d07ef2dad96d625703051e3e1c6","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Report ActionReasons when we plan to delete "orphans"

There are a few different reasons why a resource instance tracked in the
prior state might be considered an "orphan", but previously we reported
them all identically in the planned changes.

In order to help users understand the reason for a surprising planned
delete, we'll now try to specify an additional reason for the planned
deletion, covering all of the main reasons why that could happen.

This commit only introduces the new detail to the plans.Changes result,
though it also incidentally exposes it as part of the JSON plan result
in order to keep that working without returning errors in these new
cases. We'll expose this information in the human-oriented UI output in
a subsequent commit.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/a1a713cf281d9d07ef2dad96d625703051e3e1c6"},{"sha":"04f9e7148cd5cc8fa74ccd8af0c8dd2472d3a7f2","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Include deletion reasons in plan report

The core runtime is now able to specify a reason for some situations when
Terraform plans to delete a resource instance.

This commit makes that information visible in the human-oriented UI. A
previous commit already made the underlying data informing these new hints
visible as part of the machine-oriented (JSON) plan output.

This also removes the bold formatting from the existing "has moved to"
hints, because subjectively it seemed like the result was emphasizing too
many parts of the output and thus somewhat defeating the benefit of the
emphasis in trying to create additional visual hierarchy for sighted users
running Terraform in a terminal. Now only the first line containing the
main action statement will be in bold, and all of the parenthesized
follow-up notes will be unformatted.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/04f9e7148cd5cc8fa74ccd8af0c8dd2472d3a7f2"},{"sha":"1bff623fd9578df46a64ac984d64195d1c30554c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Report a warning if any moves get blocked

In most cases Terraform will be able to automatically fully resolve all
of the pending move statements before creating a plan, but there are some
edge cases where we can end up wanting to move one object to a location
where another object is already declared.

One relatively-obvious example is if someone uses "terraform state mv" in
order to create a set of resource instance bindings that could never have
arising in normal Terraform use.

A less obvious example arises from the interactions between moves at
different levels of granularity. If we are both moving a module to a new
address and moving a resource into an instance of the new module at the
same time, the old module might well have already had a resource of the
same name and so the resource move will be unresolvable.

In these situations Terraform will move the objects as far as possible,
but because it's never valid for a move "from" address to still be
declared in the configuration Terraform will inevitably always plan to
destroy the objects that didn't find a final home. To give some additional
explanation for that result, here we'll add a warning which describes
what happened.

This is not a particularly actionable warning because we don't really
have enough information to guess what the user intended, but we do at
least prompt that they might be able to use the "terraform state" family
of subcommands to repair the ambiguous situation before planning, if they
want a different result than what Terraform proposed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/1bff623fd9578df46a64ac984d64195d1c30554c"},{"sha":"d97ef10bb8cc01ab6975590ea6a410a6f586a64e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Don't return other errors if move statements are invalid

Because our validation rules depend on some dynamic results produced by
actually running the plan, we deal with moves in a "backwards" order where
we try to apply them first -- ignoring anything strange we might find --
and then validate the original statements only after planning.

An unfortunate consequence of that approach is that when the move
statements are invalid it's likely that move execution will not fully
complete, and so the generated plan is likely to be incorrect and might
well include errors resulting from the unresolved moves.

To mitigate that, here we let any move validation errors supersede all
other diagnostics that the plan phase might've generated, in the hope that
it'll help the user focus on fixing the incorrect move statements without
creating confusing by reporting errors that only appeared as a quick of
how Terraform worked around the invalid move statements earlier.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d97ef10bb8cc01ab6975590ea6a410a6f586a64e"}]

[{"sha":"f3d3994a4bf3b723df3b13e7180a592851535aa8","author":{"name":"Artem Khramov","email":"f50e3343bddce6b1d03ed216e43f2b903e34cf03@pm.me"},"message":"Port pkg/system/mknod.go to FreeBSD

Because FreeBSD uses 64-bit device nodes (see
https://reviews.freebsd.org/rS318736), Linux implementation of
`system.Mknod` & `system.Mkdev` is not sufficient.

[{"sha":"5a06072780e1323204cd7823665b3a95a0450747","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"[Old server renderer] Retry error on client (#22399)

This commit dramatically improves the performance of the hook names feature by replacing the source-map-js integration with custom mapping code built on top of sourcemap-codec. Based on my own benchmarking, this makes parsing 3-4 times faster. (The bulk of these changes are in SourceMapConsumer.js.)

While implementing this code, I also uncovered a problem with the way we were caching source-map metadata that was causing us to potential parse the same source-map multiple times. (I addressed this in a separate commit for easier reviewing. The bulk of these changes are in parseSourceAndMetadata.js.)

Altogether these changes dramatically improve the performance of the hooks parsing code.

One additional thing we could look into if the source-map download still remains a large bottleneck would be to stream it and decode the mappings array while it streams in rather than in one synchronous chunk after the full source-map has been downloaded.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/woutheijnen/react/commits/d174d063d13d428ad4002474cb560464a7f70f45"},{"sha":"3a50d95573b7ebdf723e08f6f78c99faf811da0b","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Never attach ping listeners in legacy Suspense (#22407)

I noticed a weird branch where we attach a ping listener even in legacy
mode. It's weird because this shouldn't be necessary. Fallbacks always
synchronously commit in legacy mode, so pings never happen. (A "ping" is
when a suspended promise resolves before the fallback has committed.)

It took me a moment to remember why this case exists, but it's related
to React.lazy.

There's a special case where we suspend while reconciling the children
of a Suspense boundary's inner Offscreen wrapper fiber. This happens
when a React.lazy component is a direct child of a Suspense boundary.

Suspense boundaries are implemented as multiple fibers, but they are a
single conceptual unit. The legacy mode behavior where we pretend the
suspended fiber committed as `null` won't work, because in this case the
"suspended" fiber is the inner Offscreen wrapper.

Because the contents of the boundary haven't started rendering yet (i.e.
nothing in the tree has partially rendered) we can switch to the
regular, concurrent mode behavior: mark the boundary with ShouldCapture
and enter the unwind phase.

However, even though we're switching to the concurrent mode behavior, we
don't need to attach a ping listener. So I refactored the logic so that
it doesn't escape back into the regular path.

It's not really a big deal that we attach an unncessary ping listener,
since this case is so unusual. The motivation is not performance related
— it's to make the logic clearer, because I'm about to add another case
where we trigger a Suspense boundary without attaching a ping listener.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/woutheijnen/react/commits/3a50d95573b7ebdf723e08f6f78c99faf811da0b"}]

[{"sha":"22412decaa017b359c4876983b0ae1a23e6ab40d","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Report ActionReasons when we plan to delete "orphans"

There are a few different reasons why a resource instance tracked in the
prior state might be considered an "orphan", but previously we reported
them all identically in the planned changes.

In order to help users understand the reason for a surprising planned
delete, we'll now try to specify an additional reason for the planned
deletion, covering all of the main reasons why that could happen.

This commit only introduces the new detail to the plans.Changes result,
though it also incidentally exposes it as part of the JSON plan result
in order to keep that working without returning errors in these new
cases. We'll expose this information in the human-oriented UI output in
a subsequent commit.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/22412decaa017b359c4876983b0ae1a23e6ab40d"},{"sha":"c563586ebc4cd7cefb0167a211daf70a790a2094","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Include deletion reasons in plan report

The core runtime is now able to specify a reason for some situations when
Terraform plans to delete a resource instance.

This commit makes that information visible in the human-oriented UI. A
previous commit already made the underlying data informing these new hints
visible as part of the machine-oriented (JSON) plan output.

This also removes the bold formatting from the existing "has moved to"
hints, because subjectively it seemed like the result was emphasizing too
many parts of the output and thus somewhat defeating the benefit of the
emphasis in trying to create additional visual hierarchy for sighted users
running Terraform in a terminal. Now only the first line containing the
main action statement will be in bold, and all of the parenthesized
follow-up notes will be unformatted.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/c563586ebc4cd7cefb0167a211daf70a790a2094"},{"sha":"b417aa87e53da911e70f84d319cd1dfc4e29f84d","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Report a warning if any moves get blocked

In most cases Terraform will be able to automatically fully resolve all
of the pending move statements before creating a plan, but there are some
edge cases where we can end up wanting to move one object to a location
where another object is already declared.

One relatively-obvious example is if someone uses "terraform state mv" in
order to create a set of resource instance bindings that could never have
arising in normal Terraform use.

A less obvious example arises from the interactions between moves at
different levels of granularity. If we are both moving a module to a new
address and moving a resource into an instance of the new module at the
same time, the old module might well have already had a resource of the
same name and so the resource move will be unresolvable.

In these situations Terraform will move the objects as far as possible,
but because it's never valid for a move "from" address to still be
declared in the configuration Terraform will inevitably always plan to
destroy the objects that didn't find a final home. To give some additional
explanation for that result, here we'll add a warning which describes
what happened.

This is not a particularly actionable warning because we don't really
have enough information to guess what the user intended, but we do at
least prompt that they might be able to use the "terraform state" family
of subcommands to repair the ambiguous situation before planning, if they
want a different result than what Terraform proposed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b417aa87e53da911e70f84d319cd1dfc4e29f84d"},{"sha":"f371f46459072127bbc61dab2673332e3120ad89","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Don't return other errors if move statements are invalid

Because our validation rules depend on some dynamic results produced by
actually running the plan, we deal with moves in a "backwards" order where
we try to apply them first -- ignoring anything strange we might find --
and then validate the original statements only after planning.

An unfortunate consequence of that approach is that when the move
statements are invalid it's likely that move execution will not fully
complete, and so the generated plan is likely to be incorrect and might
well include errors resulting from the unresolved moves.

To mitigate that, here we let any move validation errors supersede all
other diagnostics that the plan phase might've generated, in the hope that
it'll help the user focus on fixing the incorrect move statements without
creating confusing by reporting errors that only appeared as a quick of
how Terraform worked around the invalid move statements earlier.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/f371f46459072127bbc61dab2673332e3120ad89"}]
